Message.MsgText: ADMA0232E=ADMA0232E: Node {0} cannot be added to cluster {1} because an application currently deployed on the cluster requires Connector specification level {2}, which this node does not support
Message.Explanation: The deployed applications for this cluster require a Connector specification level that this node does not support.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the node supports the Java EE application type required by the applications currently deployed on this cluster.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5104I=ADMA5104I: The server index entry for {0} is updated successfully.
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0014E=ADMA0014E: Validation failed. {0}
Message.Explanation: A validation error occurred in preparing the application. This message is followed by a detailed error message.
Message.UserResponse: See the detailed messages for instructions on how to correct the problem.

Message.MsgText: ADMA6001I=ADMA6001I: Begin the application preparation -
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0231E=ADMA0231E: Failed to set file permissions on the file {0}.
Message.Explanation: For some reason there was a problem setting the file permissions for the file.
Message.UserResponse: Check the FFDC logs for the error.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0158I=ADMA0158I: [EJBDeploy] {0}
Message.Explanation: This message is written into the log file when the DeployEJBTask is run.
Message.UserResponse: Examine the informational message and the previous messages from the DeployEJBTask, to determine whether any corrective action is necessary.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5103E=ADMA5103E: The deletion of the configuration data for {0} from the configuration repository failed.
Message.Explanation: The uninstall procedure failed to delete the application configuration data successfully. The application is still uninstalled.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0122E=ADMA0122E: An unexpected exception occurred while getting the application {0}. Exception is {1}.
Message.Explanation: An unexpected error occurred while getting the specified application scopes.
Message.UserResponse: Review and investigate the original exception.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0013E=ADMA0013E: The dependency helper for task {0} cannot be located.
Message.Explanation: An error occurred setting up the tasks for the application.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the installation task object, if provided by the task provider, is set up correctly.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0049E=ADMA0049E: An exception occurred when getting a module for deployment descriptor {0}
Message.Explanation: This exception occurs when the unique module URI that passes into the AppManagement MBean for the getApplicationInfo or the getModuleInfo APIs does not match a module in the enterprise archive (EAR) file. The unique URI is moduleURI+ddURI
Message.UserResponse: If the getApplicationInfo or the getModuleInfo API on the AppManagement MBean is called programmatically, verify that the parameter passed in is correct.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0230I=ADMA0230I: Will retry to expand the application {0}, which previously failed to expand.
Message.Explanation: Found a marker file that indicates a binary expansion failure and expansion needs to be retried.
Message.UserResponse: No action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5102I=ADMA5102I: The configuration data for {0} from the configuration repository is deleted successfully.
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0121E=ADMA0121E: An unexpected exception occurred while getting the clusters in the cell {0}. Exception is {1}.
Message.Explanation: An unexpected error occurred while getting the clusters in the specified cell.
Message.UserResponse: Review and investigate the original exception.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0157E=ADMA0157E: The system cannot find any valid enterprise archive (EAR) wrapper extensions or an extension did not run successfully to set a new EAR file path.
Message.Explanation: This error occurs when a non-J2EE type artifact and extensions are installed to wrap the module to an EAR file before application deployment can be found or did not run successfully.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0012E=ADMA0012E: The task helper for task {0} cannot be located.
Message.Explanation: An error occurred setting up the tasks for the application.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the installation task objects, if provided by the task provider, are set up correctly.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5029E=ADMA5029E: Cluster member {0} that is defined in the cluster configuration for {1} cannot be found as a server.
Message.Explanation: The cluster.xml file for the cluster lists a cluster member that does not exist. The cluster configuration might not be valid.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0048E=ADMA0048E: An unknown module is encountered- {0}
Message.Explanation: The module parameter that passes to the getModuleInfo API of the AppManagement MBean is not valid.
Message.UserResponse: Make sure that the module parameter is a string that has a value of moduleURI+ddURI.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0156I=ADMA0156I: The enterprise archive (EAR) wrapper extension class - {0} is found and ran successfully.
Message.Explanation: An EAR wrapper extension was found to wrap the module to the EAR file.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required

Message.MsgText: ADMA0120E=ADMA0120E: An unexpected exception occurred while getting the servers in the node {0}. Exception is {1}.
Message.Explanation: An unexpected error occurred while getting the servers in the specified node.
Message.UserResponse: Review and investigate the original exception.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0011E=ADMA0011E: Error saving workspace to configuration repository.
Message.Explanation: An unexpected exception occurred when saving the changes made during an application management operation to the configuration repository.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA5028E=ADMA5028E: Server {0} on node {1} is not found in the repository.
Message.Explanation: The server with the given name does not exist under the given node.
Message.UserResponse: Correct the server name. Look for typographical errors.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0047E=ADMA0047E: An error occurred when scheduling the uninstallation for {0}
Message.Explanation: An unexpected exception occurred when uninstalling the application.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0155I=ADMA0155I: The system successfully made an enterprise archive (EAR) wrapper extension. New earFilePath: - {0}
Message.Explanation: The EAR wrapper extension is successful.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required

Message.MsgText: ADMA0010E=ADMA0010E: Validation error in task {0}. A virtual host is not specified for web module {1} with URI {2}.
Message.Explanation: The application contains a web module. The required field to specify the virtual host to install the web module does not have a value.
Message.UserResponse: Specify the virtual host for the Web module that is listed in the error message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5027E=ADMA5027E: Cluster {0} is not found in the repository.
Message.Explanation: The cluster with the given name does not exist.
Message.UserResponse: Correct the cluster name. Check for typographical errors.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0046E=ADMA0046E: Properties cannot be null for local mode.
Message.Explanation: The properties table that passes to the uninstallApplication API of the AppManagement MBean cannot be null.
Message.UserResponse: If this API is called programmatically, make sure that the properties table is not null.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0154I=ADMA0154I: A non-J2EE artifact is detected for installation. The system searches for available enterprise archive (EAR) wrapper extensions to wrap the non-J2EE artifact to an EAR file for application deployment.
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required

Message.MsgText: ADMA5026E=ADMA5026E: No valid target is specified in ObjectName {0} for module {1}.
Message.Explanation: The target server or cluster that is specified for a module in the application installation does not exist. The target server name is specified as WebSphere:cell=cellName,node=nodeName,server=serverName. The target cluster name is specified as WebSphere:cell=cellName,cluster=clusterName.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the target name is valid. Look for typographical errors.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0045E=ADMA0045E: The application name cannot be null.
Message.Explanation: The application name that passed to the checkIfAppExists or the uninstallApplication APIs of the AppManagement MBean is null.
Message.UserResponse: If these APIs are called programmatically, verify that the name is not null.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0153I=ADMA0153I: The system is starting the deployment extension step - {0}
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required

Message.MsgText: ADMA0189E=ADMA0189E: Authorization failure. The user does not have permission to update application {0}. The user must have deployer role or configurator role for the cell or for the target, or deployer role for the application.
Message.Explanation: The user does not have a proper role assigned to update the specified target.
Message.UserResponse: Confirm that the user has the proper administrative role as described in the message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5025E=ADMA5025E: The ObjectName format is incorrect for {0}.
Message.Explanation: The javax.management.ObjectName instance has domain:key=value format. The domain name for the application management function in the Application Server is WebSphere.
Message.UserResponse: Correct the ObjectName format.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0044E=ADMA0044E: An error occurred scheduling the installation for {0}
Message.Explanation: An unexpected exception occurred during installation.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0079W=ADMA0079W: The task information for: {0} cannot be found.
Message.Explanation: An unexpected exception occurred in getting the AppDeploymentTaskInfo object for a given AppDeployment task. If you see this message while testing an application installation extension, make sure that all of the classes related to the extension display in the class path.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0152E=ADMA0152E: The system failed to run the deployment extension step - {0}: {1}
Message.Explanation: This deployment step is not successful.
Message.UserResponse: Check any error logs that are specfic to the step.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0188E=ADMA0188E: Authorization failure. The user does not have permission to uninstall application {0}. The user must have deployer role or configurator role for the cell or for the target, or deployer role for the application to uninstall it.
Message.Explanation: The user does not have a proper role assigned to uninstall the specified target.
Message.UserResponse: Confirm that the user has the proper administrative role as described in the message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5024E=ADMA5024E: The cluster member {0} is specified as a target for module {1}, but the cluster {2} that {0} belongs to is not specified in the list of targets. This configuration is not valid.
Message.Explanation: An application module cannot be installed on a server that is a member of a cluster, without specifying the cluster as a target.
Message.UserResponse: Specify the cluster as a target.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0043E=ADMA0043E: {0} does not exist for installation.
Message.Explanation: The enterprise archive (EAR) file path that is provided to the installApplication API for the AppManagement MBean does not contain a file.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the file exists at the specified location.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0078W=ADMA0078W: The file: {0} cannot be deleted.
Message.Explanation: An error occurred when deleting a file or a directory.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the disk is not write-protected. If not, manually delete the file or directory that is mentioned in the error message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0151I=ADMA0151I: The system successfully ran the deployment extension step - {0}
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0187E=ADMA0187E: Authorization failure. The user does not have permission to install application {0}. The user must have deployer role or configurator role for the cell or for the targets to install/redeploy the application.
Message.Explanation: The user does not have proper role assigned to install or redeploy the the application to specified targets.
Message.UserResponse: Confirm that the user has the proper administrative role described in the message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5023E=ADMA5023E: Ambiguous specification for object {0}. Multiple objects exist with this name, at least one each under parents {1} and {2}. Specify parent {3}.
Message.Explanation: Typically this error occurs when a server name is specified as a target for the module of the application without specifying the node name. If multiple servers exist with the same name, then the value is treated as an ambiguous definition.
Message.UserResponse: Specify the parent name, for example, a node name if a server is specified.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0042E=ADMA0042E: The properties cannot be null for the installApplication API.
Message.Explanation: The properties table supplied to the installApplication API for the AppManagement MBean is null.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the properties table is not null if this API is called programmatically.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5059E=ADMA5059E: Errors in validating resource usage for application {0} - {1}
Message.Explanation: Messages before this error detail the cause of the failure. Typically the error conditions include wrong application type or wrong module targets.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0186W=ADMA0186W: An uninstall application operation failed and the configuration session could not be restored to its state before the operation was initiated. The configuration session is in an inconsistent state, and changes made in the session should be discarded.
Message.Explanation: An uninstall application operation failed, and the configuration session state could not be restored. Saving the session might result in an inconsistent configuration.
Message.UserResponse: Discard the configuration changes in the current session.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0077W=ADMA0077W: An error occurred removing the workspace. Exception: {0}
Message.Explanation: An unexpected exception occurred when saving the changes made during application installation, uninstallation, or editing. The changes might not be saved correctly. This exception is displayed only when application management functions are invoked programmatically. This error is not typically encountered during use of the wsadmin tool (except when the -local option is used) or the administration client UI.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0150E=ADMA0150E: An error occurred during the deployment extension step - {0}
Message.Explanation: An error occurred while running the deployment step.
Message.UserResponse: Check any error logs that are specific to the step.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5058I=ADMA5058I: Application and module versions are validated with versions of deployment targets.
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5022E=ADMA5022E: The target cluster {0} specified for module {1} does not exist.
Message.Explanation: A target that is specified for a module during application installation is not valid.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the specified target cluster exists.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0041E=ADMA0041E: The local enterprise archive (EAR) file path cannot be null for the installApplication API.
Message.Explanation: The EAR file path that is supplied to the installApplication API for the AppManagement MBean is null.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the EAR path is not null if this API is called programmatically.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0185W=ADMA0185W: An update application operation failed and the configuration session could not be restored to its state before the operation was initiated. The configuration session is in an inconsistent state, and changes made in the session should be discarded.
Message.Explanation: An update application operation failed, and the configuration session state could not be restored. Saving the session might result in an inconsistent configuration.
Message.UserResponse: Discard the configuration changes in the current session.

Message.MsgText: ADMA4015E=ADMA4015E: The argument {0} is not recognized.
Message.Explanation: The indicated argument is not recognized.
Message.UserResponse: Rerun the EARExpander command without the indicated argument.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0040E=ADMA0040E: Could not find an EAR, EJB JAR, or WAR (with EJBs) to process.
Message.Explanation: The deploy EJB task could not find an EAR, EJB JAR, or WAR (with EJBs) file to process.
Message.UserResponse: Verify the options specified for the deploy EJB task.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5057E=ADMA5057E: Application validation failed with an unexpected exception while checking module to server relationship: {0}
Message.Explanation: Messages before this error detail the cause of the failure. Typically the error conditions include wrong application type or wrong module targets.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA4014E=ADMA4014E: An unexpected exception occurred while attempting to collapse the contents of directory {0} to enterprise archive (EAR) file {1}. Exception: {2}
Message.Explanation: The EAR file might contain files that are not valid or access has been denied to create or read the files.
Message.UserResponse: Rerun the EARExpander command with the -verbose option to get a stack trace for the exception.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0184E=ADMA0184E: {0} is not a valid target.
Message.Explanation: The specified target server does not exist.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the target name is valid. Look for typographical errors.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5020E=ADMA5020E: The target server {0} on node {1} that is specified for module {2} does not exist.
Message.Explanation: A target that is specified for a module during application installation is not valid.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the specified target server exists.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5056E=ADMA5056E: Error in installing application {0}
Message.Explanation: Messages before this error detail the cause of the failure. Typically the error conditions include wrong application type or wrong module targets.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA4013E=ADMA4013E: An unexpected exception occurred while attempting to expand the enterprise archive (EAR) file {0} to directory {1}. Exception: {2}
Message.Explanation: The EAR file might contain files that are not valid or access has been denied to create or read the files.
Message.UserResponse: Rerun the EARExpander command with the -verbose option to get a stack trace for the exception.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0183E=ADMA0183E: Cannot delete a deployment descriptor file: {0}
Message.Explanation: The file requested to be deleted is a deployment descriptor file which cannot be deleted.
Message.UserResponse: Check that you have specified the correct file to be deleted. If there is a mistake in the deleted file name, rerun the update with the correct file to be deleted.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5055E=ADMA5055E: Errors in validating application target association for {0} - {1}
Message.Explanation: Messages before this error detail the cause of the failure. Typically the error conditions include wrong application type or wrong module targets.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0074E=ADMA0074E: A validation error occurred in task {0}. The Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name and resource authorization are not specified for module {1} with URI {2}. The data source for each container-managed persistence (CMP) bean belonging to this module is not specified. Specify the default data source for the entire module or provide the complete data source for each CMP bean belonging to this module.
Message.Explanation: The application contains a 2.x enterprise bean. The data source JNDI name and resource authorization in both the module and the container-managed persistence (CMP) bean level are not specified. You must specify the data in at least one level. If you specify the data source data in the module level, then you do not have to specify it for each CMP bean in that module unless you want to overwrite the one set in the module level. If you do not specify the data source data in the module level, then you have to specify it for each CMP bean in that module.
Message.UserResponse: Specify the data source JNDI name and resource authorization in either the module or the CMP bean level.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0182W=ADMA0182W: The JNDI name {0} specified for the message destination reference {1} does not match the JNDI name {2} of the message destination.
Message.Explanation: The JNDI name of the indicated message destination reference does not match the JNDI name that is linked by the message destination.
Message.UserResponse: Confirm that the JNDI names are correct.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0073W=ADMA0073W: Custom permissions are found in the {0} policy file. Custom permissions can compromise the integrity of Java 2 Security.
Message.Explanation: The policy file META-INF/was.policy included with the application contains custom permissions listed in the warning message. The implementation of custom permissions can weaken the integrity of the Java 2 Security permission check.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the custom permissions listed in the message are intended and update the file META-INF/was.policy in the application, if necessary.

Message.MsgText: ADMA4012E=ADMA4012E: A validation error occurred in task {0}. The Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name is not specified for the enterprise bean: {1} in module: {2}. Specify a JNDI name for the enterprise bean.
Message.Explanation: The JNDI name must have a value because an enterprise bean exists in the application.
Message.UserResponse: Specify the JNDI name for the message-driven enterprise bean in the task that is listed in the error message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5054E=ADMA5054E: The InstalledOptionalPackage deployment task failed on {0}: {1}
Message.Explanation: This message indicates that the InstalledOptionalPackage installation task failed during application installation. Prior messages detail the cause of this failure.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA4011E=ADMA4011E: A validation error occurred in task {0}. The Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name is not specified for message destination object {1} in module {2}.
Message.Explanation: A message destination reference exists in the application. The JNDI name field that is required to bind the reference does not have a value.
Message.UserResponse: Specify the JNDI name for the reference in the task that is listed in the error message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0181E=ADMA0181E: Comparing security policy failed with unknown exception. Exception is {0}.
Message.Explanation: Comparing security policy had failed with unknown exception.
Message.UserResponse: Investigate the exception.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5053I=ADMA5053I: The library references for the installed optional package are created.
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA4010W=ADMA4010W: Both the listener port and the Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name are specified for the enterprise bean: {0} in module {1}. Specify only one value, either the listener port or the JNDI name, for the enterprise bean.
Message.Explanation: Specify either the listener port and the JNDI name for the message-driven enterprise bean, but not both of them.
Message.UserResponse: Specify either the listener port or the JNDI name for the message-driven enterprise bean in the listed task.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0072E=ADMA0072E: Your application contains policy permissions that are in the filter policy. These permissions are security sensitive and can compromise the integrity of the system. Remove these permissions from your policy file before attempting to install your application again.
Message.Explanation: Application Server attempts to prevent applications from performing security-sensitive operations, like calling the System.exit method, replacing the Java 2 Security manager, and replacing the Java 2 Security policy. If the application is granted the all permissions (java.security.AllPermission), the Java 2 Security permission checks are effectively disabled, which can compromise the integrity of the system.
Message.UserResponse: Review the application policy, which is located in the EAR/META-INF/was.policy file, remove the security-sensitive permissions and grant the application the permissions that are required only.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5052W=ADMA5052W: A value that is not valid {0} is detected for the class loading mode. The default, PARENT_FIRST, is used.
Message.Explanation: The value for the class loading mode must be specified using the constants that are defined in the AppConstants class.
Message.UserResponse: Make sure that the class loading mode has one of the predefined values.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0071W=ADMA0071W: An attempt to perform security policy filtering failed. An unexpected exception occurred {0}
Message.Explanation: An error occurred while performing security policy filtering. Security filtering is not performed.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required if no security concerns exist. Otherwise, validate your configuration.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0180E=ADMA0180E: Comparing security policy failed with PrivilegedActionException.
Message.Explanation: Some of the action to compare the security policy could not be performed because of the lack of privilege.
Message.UserResponse: Confirm that there is enough privilege to perform the compare the security policy.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5051W=ADMA5051W: An unacceptable value {0} for the class loader policy is detected. The default MULTIPLE is used.
Message.Explanation: The value for the class loader policy must be specified using the constants that are defined in the AppConstants class.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the class loader policy has one of the predefined values.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0070W=ADMA0070W: Security policy filtering cannot be performed: An error occurred getting the repository context for a cell in the workspace.
Message.Explanation: An error occurred while searching for the filter policy in the configuration. Security filtering is not performed.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required if no security concerns exist. Otherwise, validate your configuration.

Message.MsgText: ADMA8019E=ADMA8019E: The resources that are assigned to the application are beyond the deployment target scope. Resources are within the deployment target scope if they are defined at the cell, node, server, or application level when the deployment target is a server, or at the cell, cluster, or application level when the deployment target is a cluster. Assign resources that are within the deployment target scope of the application or confirm that these resources assignments are correct as specified.
Message.Explanation: Resources that are assigned to application are beyond deployment target scope.
Message.UserResponse: Click Cancel to return to the previous step and correct JNDI assignments. Because Validate installation option FAIL is chosen, you cannot continue beyond this step. Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0132E=ADMA0132E: The operation {0} that is specfied for updating application {1} is not valid.
Message.Explanation: The operation type is not valid in the updateApplication API.
Message.UserResponse: Specify a valid operation type: add, addupdate, update, or delete.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0168E=ADMA0168E: Attempt to remove last module {0}.
Message.Explanation: The specified module is the last module in the application. Application Server cannot remove all of the modules from the application.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0059E=ADMA0059E: An incorrect task data format is detected. The resource authorization data is missing in module {0}
Message.Explanation: An error occurred in preparing the application. The default connection factory for a Java archive (JAR) file contains incomplete data.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA6010I=ADMA6010I: The tasks are {0}
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0240E=ADMA0240E: The application contains EJB content in web module {0}. This module can not be targeted for web server {1}.
Message.Explanation: EJB content within a web module is not recognized on an HTTP server.
Message.UserResponse: Target the web module to at least 1 application server and remove targeting of this module to any web server.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5112E=ADMA5112E: An error occurred creating an activation plan for the application - {0}
Message.Explanation: An activation plan defines dependency of Java Platform, Enterprise Edition application modules on WebSphere runtime components. An unexpected error occurred while deducing this dependency.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0131E=ADMA0131E: The path to content must be specified when the contenttype value is partialapp for updating an application.
Message.Explanation: The content path is null in the updateApplication API.
Message.UserResponse: Specify the pathToContents value in the updateApplication API.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0167E=ADMA0167E: File {0} does not exist for {1} operation.
Message.Explanation: The file that is specified by the URL does not exist in the application. The specified operation cannot be performed.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the specified URL is correct or that the operation is correct.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5003I=ADMA5003I: The JavaServer Pages (JSP) files in the Web Archive (WAR) {0} compiled successfully.
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates that the JSP files in the specified WAR compiled without errors.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5039E=ADMA5039E: The node name cannot be null.
Message.Explanation: The node name that passed in as a parameter to the removeAllAppsFromNode API cannot be null.
Message.UserResponse: If the removeAllAppsFromNode API on the AppManagement MBean is called programmatically, make sure that the node name that is passed in is not null.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0058E=ADMA0058E: An incorrect task data value for resource authorization exists in module {0}.
Message.Explanation: An error occurred in preparing the application. The resource authorization value for a Java archive (JAR) file is not specified correctly. The correct values are per application or container.
Message.UserResponse: Enter the correct value for the resource authorization in the JAR file that is specified in the error message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5111E=ADMA5111E: The deployment.xml file could not be found in the expanded application directory while installing as a system application
Message.Explanation: Deployment.xml file does not exist
Message.UserResponse: Make sure the deployment.xml file exists

Message.MsgText: ADMA0130E=ADMA0130E: The content type {0} that is specified for updating {1} is not valid.
Message.Explanation: The content type can be file, module, partialapp or app.
Message.UserResponse: Change the content type that passes to the updateApplication API.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0166E=ADMA0166E: Duplicate file {0} for {1} operation.
Message.Explanation: The file that is specified by the URL already exists in the application. The specified operation cannot be performed.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the specified URL is correct or that the operation is correct. Use update instead of add.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5038I=ADMA5038I: The system Completed the backup of the application at {0}
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5002E=ADMA5002E: Application binaries cannot be saved in {0}: {1}
Message.Explanation: As part of the application installation, the application enterprise archive (EAR) file is saved in the Application Server configuration repository. This error message is displayed during installation if the enterprise archive (EAR) file cannot be saved.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that enough disk space is available to save the EAR file, and check the file permissions.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0021E=ADMA0021E: An error occurred in compiling JavaServer Pages (JSP) files - {0}
Message.Explanation: An error occurred while compiling JSP files in a Web Archive (WAR) file.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the JSP files do not have any code that does not compile.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0057E=ADMA0057E: An incorrect task data format is detected: the user and password data is missing in module {0}
Message.Explanation: An error occurred in preparing the application. The default data source for a Java archive (JAR) file has incomplete data.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA5110I=ADMA5110I: The application {0} is installed as a hidden application and will not be exposed via administrative interfaces such as GUI client, wsadmin or MBean Java API. In order to perform management operations on this application, the application name must be known.
Message.Explanation: This information message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0165E=ADMA0165E: Content does not exist at the path specified {0} for a partialapp update.
Message.Explanation: The specified content does not exist.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the content path is correct.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5001I=ADMA5001I: The application binaries are saved in {0}
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5037I=ADMA5037I: The system is starting to back up the application at {0}
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0020E=ADMA0020E: An error occurred backing up the enterprise archive (EAR) file - {0}
Message.Explanation: An error occurred while copying the EAR file to the configuration repository.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0056E=ADMA0056E: An incorrect task data format is detected; the Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) data is missing in module {0}
Message.Explanation: An error occurred in preparing the application. The default data source for a Java archive (JAR) file is not specified.
Message.UserResponse: Specify the default data source for the JAR file that is specified in the error message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0164W=ADMA0164W: Failed to load the systemapps.xml file on cell {0}, node {1}.
Message.Explanation: The systemapps.xml file did not load.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the cell name and node name are correct.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5036E=ADMA5036E: An exception {0} occurred while copying session manager settings from server {1}.
Message.Explanation: The previous message details the cause of this problem.
Message.UserResponse: Read the previous message to understand the probable cause.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0055E=ADMA0055E: An error occurred getting task {0}
Message.Explanation: This exception occurs when a task that is scheduled to perform one of the application installation activities cannot be instantiated. Installation is halted as a result of this exception.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0163E=ADMA0163E: Resource validation is not initialized.
Message.Explanation: The call to initialize the resource validation is not performed.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0199E=ADMA0199E: The system cannot complete the operation with autolink enabled. All modules must share one common target to enable autolink support.
Message.Explanation: To use autolink for an EJB reference, each module in the application must share at least one common target.
Message.UserResponse: Specify a common target for each module or disable the autolink option. Then, rerun the same operation.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5035E=ADMA5035E: The copy operation on the session manager of {0} failed, as the copy is {1}.
Message.Explanation: The copy made of the session manager settings is not of type SessionManager.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0054E=ADMA0054E: An exception occurred checking application existence - {0}
Message.Explanation: An unexpected exception occurred in checking the existence of the application during application uninstallation so the uninstallation is not proceeding. This problem can also occur if the application to uninstall does not exist in the configuration.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the application name that is supplied to the uninstall action is correct.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0162W=ADMA0162W: The resource assignment with name {0} is found within scope of module {1} with URI {2} deployed to target {3}, but of wrong resource type {4}. The expected resource type is {5}.
Message.Explanation: The resource is not found on the deployment target.
Message.UserResponse: Make sure that the resource Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name is correct for the resource.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5034W=ADMA5034W: The server {0} mentioned in the copy.sessionmgr.servername options for installation does not exist in the configuration.
Message.Explanation: The server name is not valid.
Message.UserResponse: Make sure that the server exists.

Message.MsgText: ADMA9009E=ADMA9000E: You cannot install an application across multiple security domains. Make sure that all the deployment targets belong to the same security domain.
Message.Explanation: Application cannot be installed accross multiple security domains.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that user is not installing this application accorss multiple security domains.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0509I=ADMA0509I: The pureQuery bind operation on application {0} completed successfully. Exit code: {1}
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0053E=ADMA0053E: An error occurred closing the enterprise archive (EAR) file {0}
Message.Explanation: This exception occurs during application installation processing if the enterprise archive (EAR) file gets locked because of an unexpected error, and cannot be closed. Application installation is stopped when this error occurs.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0089E=ADMA0089E: The AppManagement MBean is not found.
Message.Explanation: If the AppManagement MBean is a node agent or application server, then the AppManagement MBean is not activated by default.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0161W=ADMA0161W: The resource assignment with name {0} is not found within scope of module {1} with URI {2} that is deployed to target {3}.
Message.Explanation: The resource is not found on the deployment target.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the resource Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) name is correct for the resource.

Message.MsgText: ADMA9008E=ADMA9008E: The application server is running in a restricted mode. The {0} application management operation is not available in your application server installation.
Message.Explanation: The application cannot be installed or updated without a full application server license.
Message.UserResponse: Do not call the application programming interfaces (API) for application management that update applications in this installation environment.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0197E=ADMA0197E: The application cannot be updated with the {0} file because the application server cannot expand the {1} URI as an archive file. Either the URI does not resolve to an archive file or the archive file is corrupted.
Message.Explanation: An archive file in a deployed application cannot be opened. The file URI that is specified in the error message might resolve to a file that is not an archive file in the deployed application. The archive file also might be corrupted.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the contents of the files that are used to update the application are consistent with the application archive that is being updated. Also, make sure that the deployed application archive is not corrupted.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0508I=ADMA0508I: The pureQuery bind operation on application {0} did not complete successfully. Exit code: {1}
Message.Explanation: The pureQuery bind operation encountered a problem. This informational message indicates the program status. Prior messages in the command output give details of the problem.
Message.UserResponse: Check the command output for the cause of the problem.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5033E=ADMA5033E: The target server {0} specified for {2} is a part of cluster {1}, but cluster {1} is not specified in the list of targets.
Message.Explanation: A module cannot be installed on a cluster member without also specifying the cluster as a target.
Message.UserResponse: Specify the cluster as a module target also.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5069E=ADMA5069E: The installation of application {0} failed. This application was in the middle of a full update and therefore is uninstalled from the configuration session. Discard your current configuration session immediately to recover the application. Do not save changes to the WebSphere Application Server configuration repository. The application is not uninstalled from this repository. Until the current configuration session is discarded you do not see this application in the current session.
Message.Explanation: Prior messages detail the cause of this failure.
Message.UserResponse: Read the previous message to rectify the problem.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0088E=ADMA0088E: An unacceptable usage of {0} has occurred. Operation {0} can be called only in the local mode of the AppManagement MBean.
Message.Explanation: Some of the application management functions can be called only if the AppManagement MBean runs in local mode, that is without connecting to a Java Management Extentions (JMX) process.
Message.UserResponse: If this API is called programmatically, make sure that the AppManagementProxy object is created using the getLocalProxy method.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0196W=ADMA0196W: Environment entry {1} in module {0} does not have a value.
Message.Explanation: The indicated environment entry does not have a value. A value is required when no injection targets are specified. Environment entries without a value will be ignored (with a warning) during runtime.
Message.UserResponse: Specify a value or injection targets for the indicated environment entry.

Message.MsgText: ADMA9007I=ADMA9007I: The application server is running in a restricted mode under the {0} product.
Message.Explanation: The product name is registered.
Message.UserResponse: No action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5032W=ADMA5032W: The target {0} is specified more than once in {1}. Ignoring {2}
Message.Explanation: The same target that is specified multiple times for the same module is treated as a single target.
Message.UserResponse: Remove the duplicates from the target name.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0087W=ADMA0087W: [EJBDeploy] {0}
Message.Explanation: This message is written into the log file when an EJBDeploy warning is encountered.
Message.UserResponse: Examine this message and any previous messages from the EJBDeploy program, to determine whether any corrective action is necessary.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0160E=ADMA0160E: The target scope that is passed to the listApplications has incorrect format {0}.
Message.Explanation: The target scope must be "WebSphere:cell=myCell,node=myNode", "WebSphere:cell=myCell,node=myNode,server=myServer" or "WebSphere:cell=myCell,cluster=myCluster".
Message.UserResponse: Correct the syntax of the target.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5068I=ADMA5068I: The resource validation for application {0} completed successfully, but warnings occurred during validation.
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0507I=ADMA0507I: The SQLJ operation on application {0} completed successfully. Exit code: {1}
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0195W=ADMA0195W: Environment entry {1} in module {0} does not have a type.
Message.Explanation: The indicated environment entry does not specify a type. A type is required when no injection targets are specified.
Message.UserResponse: Specify a type or injection targets for the indicated environment entry.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0050W=ADMA0050W: Role name is empty for security role {0}.
Message.Explanation: The RunAsBinding element in the applications bindings file (ibm-application-bnd.xmi or ibm-application-bnd.xml file for EE5) references a security role element in the application deployment descriptor (application.xml) that does not exist.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the security role exists in the application deployment descriptor file.

Message.MsgText: ADMA9006E=ADMA9006E: The application failed to install. The {0} application is not licensed to be installed in this server under the {1} product.
Message.Explanation: The application is not licensed to be installed on this server.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the application is licensed.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5067I=ADMA5067I: Resource validation for application {0} completed successfully.
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0506I=ADMA0506I: The SQLJ operation on application {0} did not complete successfully. Exit code: {1}
Message.Explanation: The SQLJ operation encountered a problem. This informational message indicates the program status. Prior messages in the command output give details of the problem.
Message.UserResponse: Check the command output for the cause of the problem.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5031E=ADMA5031E: The system cannot load {0} document for the object at {1}.
Message.Explanation: The document is corrupted or empty.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0086E=ADMA0086E: [EJBDeploy] {0}
Message.Explanation: This message is written into the log file when an EJBDeploy error is encountered.
Message.UserResponse: Examine this message and any previous messages from the EJBDeploy program, to determine the source of the problem.

Message.MsgText: ADMA9005E=ADMA9005E: Cannot associate Access Ids {0} with mapped user/group {1} because of incompatible length.
Message.Explanation: Access ids should have one to one mapping to the user/group.
Message.UserResponse: Validate the entries and retry.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0194E=ADMA0194E: Authorization failure. The user does not have permission to start/stop application {0}. The user must have operator role of the applocation.
Message.Explanation: The user does not have a proper role assigned to operate the specified application.
Message.UserResponse: Confirm that the user has the proper administrative role described in the message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5030E=ADMA5030E: No deployment object is found in the deployment document for {0}.
Message.Explanation: The deployment.xml file for the given deployment is empty or not valid.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA5066E=ADMA5066E: Error validate application {0} : {1}.
Message.Explanation: See messages for cause of error.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0505E=ADMA0505E: An exception occurred while accessing a temporary output file. The file name is: {0}
Message.Explanation: An exception occurred while opening or writing a temporary output file.
Message.UserResponse: Examine the linked exception for the cause.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0085E=ADMA0085E: A validation error occurred in task {0}. Application name, {1}, is not valid. An application name cannot begin with a dot, cannot have leading or trailing spaces, cannot contain "]]>", and cannot contain any of the following characters: \ / , # $ @ : ; " * ? < > | = + & % ''
Message.Explanation: The specified application name contains an unacceptable character. An application name cannot begin with a dot, cannot have leading or trailing spaces, cannot contain "]]>", and cannot contain any of the following characters: backward slash (\), slash (/), comma (,), number sign (#), dollar ($), at sign (@), colon (:), semicolon (;), quotation mark ("), asterisk (*), question mark (?), greater than sign (>), less than sign (<), pipe (|), equal sign (=), plus (+), ampersand (&), percent (%), or single quotation mark (').
Message.UserResponse: Specify an application name that does not contain any of these unacceptable characters.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0504W=ADMA0504W: A duplicate profile name was found. The short profile name is: {0}. The input profile name is: {1}.
Message.Explanation: During SQLJ processing a duplicate profile name was found.
Message.UserResponse: Check the input list of profile names for duplicate names.

Message.MsgText: ADMA9004E=ADMA9004E: The {0} external binding file cannot be found.
Message.Explanation: The external binding file cannot be found.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the binding file is available on the file system.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0193E=ADMA0193E: Authorization failure. The user does not have permission to update the application {0}. The user must have deployer role or configurator role for the cell or deployer role of the application.
Message.Explanation: The user does not have a proper role assigned to manage the specified target.
Message.UserResponse: Confirm that the user has the proper administrative role described in the message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5065E=ADMA5065E: Exception in FileMergeTask {0}.
Message.Explanation: See the exception for causes of the error.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA0084E=ADMA0084E: The archive {0} to wrap is not a module of type JAR or WAR.
Message.Explanation: The specified application file is not a valid JAR or WAR file.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the correct application file is entered.

Message.MsgText: ADMA9003E=ADMA9003E: The {0} destination directory cannot be found in the enterprise archive (EAR) file.
Message.Explanation: The destination directory for the external binding file must be part of the application.
Message.UserResponse: Make sure that the destination directory for the binding file is specified in the EAR file.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0192E=ADMA0192E: Authorization failure. The user does not have permission to access the resource {0}. The user must have {1} role to access {2}.
Message.Explanation: The user does not a have proper role assigned to access the specified resource.
Message.UserResponse: Confirm that the user has the proper administrative role described in the error message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5064I=ADMA5064I: FileMergeTask completed successfully for {0}.
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0503E=ADMA0503E: An exception occurred while accessing an input file. The file name is: {0}
Message.Explanation: An exception occurred while opening or reading an input file.
Message.UserResponse: If the file was not found, verify that the file name is correct.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0083E=ADMA0083E: The file or directory {0} that is specified as an enterprise archive (EAR) file is not valid.
Message.Explanation: The application specified is not a valid EAR file.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the correct application file is entered. Otherwise, validate your application using the Application Server Toolkit.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5063W=ADMA5063W: Wrong input for recycle behavior. {0} is specified as recycle option, but modules to recycle are not supplied using key {0}.
Message.Explanation: Recycle option does not match input.
Message.UserResponse: If the problem persists, additional information might be available if you search for the message ID on the following Web sites: WebSphere Application Server Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/was/support/ WebSphere Application Server for z/OS Support page: http://www.ibm.com/software/webservers/appserv/zos_os390/support/ .

Message.MsgText: ADMA9002E=ADMA9002E: Installation of application failed because LightweightLocal is set in {0} and target node is prior to 6.1
Message.Explanation: This informational message indicates the program status.
Message.UserResponse: No user action is required.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0191E=ADMA0191E: Authorization failure. The user does not have permission to access the resource {0}. The user must have monitor role for the cell, target node or the application.
Message.Explanation: The user does not have a proper role assigned to access the specified resource.
Message.UserResponse: Confirm that the user has the proper administrative role described in the message.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0502E=ADMA0502E: An exception occurred while updating the enterprise archive (EAR) file in the workspace. The SQLJ customization results were not stored, however, if SQLJ binding was performed, then packages in the database have been modified. The application name is: {0} The workspace EAR file is: {1}
Message.Explanation: An exception occurred while storing the results of SQLJ processing to the enterprise archive (EAR) file in the workspace. The EAR file modifications were not saved. The SQLJ processing may have created or changed corresponding packages in the database.
Message.UserResponse: Retry the application management command.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0082E=ADMA0082E: Your application contains the following incompatible Java archive (JAR) or Web application archive (WAR) file:{0}. Correct the file before trying the operation again.
Message.Explanation: Typically, this error is displayed when a J2EE 1.2 application enterprise archive (EAR) file contains a J2EE 1.3 module.
Message.UserResponse: Verify that the EAR file is a J2EE-compliant EAR file.

Message.MsgText: ADMA5062W=ADMA5062W: An error occurred while reusing the existing deployment.xml file. The original deployment settings are not reused."
Message.Explanation: A problem occurred getting the existing deployment resource.
Message.UserResponse: Edit the application to restore any previous deployment settings.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0081W=ADMA0081W: The 1.2.x enterprise application does not contain a Java 2 Security policy. Your application might not run after it is installed.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0208E=ADMA0208E: The Enterprise Archive (EAR) contains an unsupported xmi format bindings or extensions file.
Message.Explanation:
This error occurs when an EAR has a version that is associated with Java Enterprise Edition (Java EE) 5 or later and the EAR has IBM bindings and extensions files in an older XMI format. When an EAR has a Java EE 5 or later specific version, the bindings and extensions files must not use the old XMI format. Instead, the bindings and extensions files must use the new XML format.
IBM bindings and extensions files in the older XMI format have a .xmi file extension. IBM bindings and extensions files in the new XML format have a .xml file extension.
Message.UserResponse:
Either revert the application version to a pre-Java EE 5 value or remove the bindings and extensions files. Important: Do not rename the bindings and extensions files to change the file extension from .xmi to .xml.
If you remove the bindings and extensions files, the files can be regenerated using the application deployment process. Also, you can regenerate the bindings and extensions files using application development tools.

Message.MsgText: ADMA0207E=ADMA0207E: Module {0} contains an unsupported xmi format bindings or extensions file.
Message.Explanation:
This error occurs when a module has a version that is associated with Java Enterprise Edition (Java EE) 5 or later and the module has IBM bindings and extensions files in an older XMI format. Module versions that are specific to Java EE 5 are 2.5 for Web archive (WAR) files and 3.0 for Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) Java archive (JAR) files. When a module has a Java EE 5 or later specific version, the bindings and extensions files of that module must not use the old XMI format. Instead, the bindings and extensions files of the module must use the new XML format.
IBM bindings and extensions files in the older XMI format have a .xmi file extension. IBM bindings and extensions files in the new XML format have a .xml file extension.
Message.UserResponse:
Either revert the module version to a pre-Java EE 5 value or remove the bindings and extensions files from the module. Important: Do not rename the bindings and extensions files to change the file extension from .xmi to .xml.
Note: The error is specific to individual modules. When you fix this problem, only update the specific modules that are exhibiting the problem.
If you remove the bindings and extensions files, the files can be regenerated using the application deployment process. Also, you can regenerate the bindings and extensions files using application development tools.
